summary.name: gapminder-health-income.csv
summary.dataset_description: This dataset contains information about the income, health, population and region of different countries.

properties.description: The income of the country in US dollars.
The life expectancy of the country in years.
The region where the country is located.

goals.question: What is the relationship between income and health?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of income vs health
goals.rationale: This will help us understand if there is a correlation between income and health, and if countries with higher income have better health outcomes.

goals.question: What is the distribution of population across different regions?
goals.visualization: bar chart of population by region
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the population distribution across different regions and identify regions with high or low population density.

goals.question: What is the average income by region?
goals.visualization: box plot of income by region
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the income distribution across different regions and identify regions with higher or lower income levels.

goals.question: What is the distribution of health across different regions?
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the health distribution across different regions and identify regions with better or worse health outcomes.

goals.question: What is the relationship between population and income?
goals.visualization: scatter plot of population vs income
goals.rationale: This will help us understand if there is a correlation between population and income, and if countries with higher population have higher income levels.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.scatter(data['income'], data['health'])
    plt.xlabel('Income')
    plt.ylabel('Health')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between income and health?', wrap=True)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    else:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    population_by_region = data.groupby('region')['population'].sum()
    ax = population_by_region.plot(kind='bar')
    ax.set_xlabel('Region')
    ax.set_ylabel('Population')
    ax.set_title('What is the distribution of population across different regions?')
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    for i, v in enumerate(population_by_region):
        ax.text(i, v, str(v), ha='center', va='bottom')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
